The Rivers State government has declared that the third coronavirus case in the state is a 61-year old manager of a hotel located in Port Harcourt. It said the victim was taken care of his boss, owner of hotel, who return from Abuja in February and died mysteriously, thereby raising the suspicion that he might have died of coronavirus. Addressing newsmen in Port Harcourt, the state Commissioner for Health, Professor Princewill Chike, said the Rapid Response Team of the Minister of Health has already started tracing the contacts of the victim. Chike said: “The latest case is a hotel manager. His boss returned from Abuja this February. The Rapid Response Team was notified of sudden and mysterious death his boss, the hotel owner last week. The team decided to place all his contacts under watch. Samples were collected from the hotel manager for COVID tests and his result turned in yesterday evening, positive. “He has been evacuated to the treatment centre and we have commenced treatment at the centre. All other contacts and highlights will be adequately followed up, including necessary environmental decontamination as the case may be. “Contact-tracing has already commenced and samples will be collected from high-risk contacts for analysis. Communication and community engagement will continue unabated as usual. Be rest assured that no stone would be left unturned. I am sure a lot of question will arise why this time around. “As I mentioned earlier, the Rivers State government-owned Emergency Operations Centre is and will remain a response point with dedicated and experienced health officers and volunteers doing their best to conquer this pandemic in the part of the world.” 